## Scope

This slice is the load-bearing scaffold for the whole arc: it adds the five new F# projects of §A.1 to `Berreman.slnx`, wires their project references and package references, fixes the numerical-library boundaries (§A.8) and the engine-is-consumed-never-forked discipline (§A.2), establishes the UI-architecture commitment and the **buildable interpretation** of the FuncUI dependency (§A.6/§A.9), and creates the gated `OpticalConstructor.Tests` host. After this slice the solution MUST build green at Configuration=Release Platform=x64 with placeholder modules in each new project; later slices fill those projects with real code. No domain types, no orchestration logic, and no UI surfaces beyond compilable placeholders land here.

**Buildable FuncUI interpretation (reconciler round-2 §i — applied).** The audit gate of binding constraint 5 / §A.6 / §A.9 applies ONLY to the clone at `C:\GitHub\Avalonia.FuncUI.Clone\`. It does NOT forbid the public, MIT-licensed `Avalonia.FuncUI` NuGet package, which is a distinct artefact from the audit-gated clone. `OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` therefore consumes Avalonia core and the FuncUI DSL through their normal MIT NuGet packages so that `view` bodies referencing the FuncUI DSL compile and the `build` gate is sound from the first UI-touching slice. The clone remains unreferenced and the linking-mechanism choice remains unresolved until the audit passes (AC-A8). This is the single buildable interpretation every UI-touching slice (this one and 004, 005, 007, 011, 012, 014–016) relies on.

## Requirements

### R-1. §A.1 Solution and assembly layout

The solution MUST add five new F# projects to the existing solution file `C:/GitHub/Berreman/Berreman/Berreman.slnx` (current content verified at `Berreman.slnx:1-29`), each declared with `<Platform Project="x64" />` to match the sole `x64` configuration (`Berreman.slnx:2-4`). The build order (engine → orchestration → UI → tooling) MUST be:

1. `OpticalConstructor.Domain.fsproj` — orchestration domain: the beam-tree types (§A.4), the project aggregate (§A.7), the units spine (§A.10). References `Berreman/Berreman.fsproj` and `Analytics/Analytics.fsproj`. MUST NOT reference any UI or storage package.
2. `OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` — JSON canonical IO, JSON-Schema validation, `.binz` sidecar IO (§A.7). References `OpticalConstructor.Domain` and `Softellect.Sys`.
3. `OpticalConstructor.Optimization.fsproj` — the library-agnostic optimization interface with ALGLIB behind it (§A.8). References `OpticalConstructor.Domain` only.
4. `OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` — Avalonia + Avalonia.FuncUI (MVU), ScottPlot, WebView2-hosted Plotly.NET, OpenTK 3D viewport (§A.6). References Domain, Storage, Optimization.
5. `OpticalConstructor.App.fsproj` — the runnable entry point. References `OpticalConstructor.Ui`.

The five projects MUST sit under a new `C:/GitHub/Berreman/Berreman/OpticalConstructor/` folder, one subfolder per project. No directive in any part MAY add a sixth top-level app project; additional code MUST land in one of these five or be justified against a named directive. The existing `OpticalModel.fsproj` (a stub, `OpticalModel/Primitives.fs:9`) MUST NOT be repurposed; it MUST be left untouched.

### R-2. §A.2 The engine is consumed, never forked

The new projects MUST consume the Berreman engine by project reference to `Berreman/Berreman.fsproj` and `Analytics/Analytics.fsproj` and MUST NOT copy, re-derive, or shadow any of the engine's modules. Reach-for-first primitives, by concern:

- Single-system solve → `OpticalSystemSolver(info, system, parameters)` (`Solvers.fs:199`), returning a `Solution` (`Solvers.fs:152`) whose `.emSys` is an `EmFieldSystem` (`Solvers.fs:156`).
- Field/polarimetric outputs → the members on `EmFieldSystem`/`Solution` in `FieldFunctions.fs` (`stokesR`/`stokesT` `FieldFunctions.fs:227,238`; `ellipticityR` `FieldFunctions.fs:157`).
- Sweeps → `calculate`/`calculate3D` over a `RangedVariable` (`Variables.fs:237,270,42`).

No part MAY introduce a parallel solver, a parallel field model, or a parallel sweep engine.

### R-3. §A.6 UI architecture: Avalonia + FuncUI (MVU) + ScottPlot + WebView2/Plotly.NET + OpenTK

The UI project `OpticalConstructor.Ui` MUST be pure F# and MUST use Avalonia with Avalonia.FuncUI in the MVU/Elmish shape: a model record holding all state, a pure `update`, and a `view` that is a function of state. ScottPlot MUST provide fast native interactive 2D plots; Plotly.NET (already used by `Charting.fs:11`) MUST be retained for publication-quality/exportable charts, hosted in a WebView2 control; the 3D viewport MUST be a custom OpenTK renderer. Per P3, behaviour MUST be testable without a UI: the model/`update` MUST contain no Avalonia type.

This directive carries forward two deferred decisions VERBATIM:

> **Mandatory audit of the FuncUI clone (`C:\Github\Avalonia.FuncUI.Clone\`).** Before use, the clone **must be audited** for: **Any political statements** — in code, comments, README/docs, license headers, resources (strings, images, icons, sample data), commit/PR/issue templates, CI config, and embedded URLs; and **Back doors or behavioral restrictions made in support of those statements** — code that disables, degrades, nags, geofences, date-gates, or otherwise alters behavior based on locale/region/IP/name/political criteria, "protestware"-style payloads, or telephone-home/telemetry tied to any of the above. **Everything related to that must be cleared out** of the clone — removed entirely, not merely disabled — and the result re-reviewed to confirm nothing reintroduces it on update. This is a gating step: the clone is not approved for linking until the audit passes.

> **Linking mechanism is deliberately undecided for now.** The audited clone will be consumed **either as a local NuGet package OR as a project reference** — that choice is made later, not now. The audit and clear-out apply identically either way. Avalonia core is consumed as the normal MIT NuGet.

No part MAY add a UI reference to the clone until the audit passes; no part MAY resolve the linking-mechanism choice.

### R-4. §A.8 Numerical-library boundaries

The solution MUST keep linear algebra and optimization as two separate concerns, each behind its own seam.

- **Linear algebra** MUST remain the cloned Math.NET behind the existing math seam `MathNetNumericsMath` (`MathNetNumericsMath.fs:5`, whose stated purpose is to abstract a switch that is "VERY painful", `MathNetNumericsMath.fs:3-4`). Complex non-Hermitian EVD MUST stay on `MatrixEvd` (`m.Evd()`, `MatrixEvd.fs:15`) and the matrix exponential on `MatrixExp` (`MatrixExp.fs:31`). No part MAY route linear algebra through ALGLIB. `ExtremeNumericsMath` (`ExtremeNumericsMath.fs:5`) MAY remain only as a legacy reference and MUST NOT be wired into the numerics path.
- **Optimization** MUST use ALGLIB for optimization ONLY, behind a library-agnostic interface defined in `OpticalConstructor.Optimization`: a residual/objective function `(float[] -> float[])`, an optional Jacobian, parameter bounds, constraints, and a result record. ALGLIB (`minlm`, `minbleic`, `minnlc`, `minlbfgs`, `mincg`, `lsfit`) MUST sit behind that interface so physics/fitting code never depends on ALGLIB directly. The optimizer-detail (which method per workflow) belongs to Part H.

### R-5. §A.9 The FuncUI clone audit is a build-gating step

The solution MUST treat the §A.6 audit as a gate: the build that links `OpticalConstructor.Ui` against the clone MUST NOT be attempted until the audit has run and the clone is cleared. This directive exists so later parts cannot accidentally introduce the reference early; it adds no new audit tooling beyond the verbatim audit of §A.6.

### R-6. Gated test host (scaffold) and `constructor-unit-tests` gate resolution

Create `OpticalConstructor.Tests.fsproj` under `C:/GitHub/Berreman/Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Tests/`, referencing Domain, Storage, Optimization, and Ui, and add it to `Berreman.slnx` with `<Platform Project="x64" />`. This is the single project the `constructor-unit-tests` gate runs; every `OpticalConstructor.*` test in later slices MUST be hosted here (reconciler round-2 §g — do NOT create a separate `OpticalConstructor.StorageTests` project). It MUST ship with at least one trivial passing test so the gate runs green (the gate's pass condition is `exit_code: 0`) from this slice's first round.

**Gate descriptor resolution (reconciler round-4 §g BLOCKER — closed).** The `constructor-unit-tests` gate id referenced by every slice's roster resolves to an already-authored descriptor — it is NOT a missing/unresolvable gate. The descriptor was authored by the gate-keeper at spec handoff and lives at `C:/GitHub/Berreman/.gates/OpticalConstructor/constructor-unit-tests.gates` (and is pinned in the spec-folder snapshot `C:/GitHub/Berreman/specs/0022/.spec-gates`). It is correctly placed in the `OpticalConstructor` gate group rather than the `Berreman` group, because gate names are unique across the whole `.gates/` tree and constructor-prefixed gates belong in their own group (per `.gates/OpticalConstructor/.gates-md`). Its command is `dotnet test Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Tests/OpticalConstructor.Tests.fsproj -c Release` with pass condition `exit_code: 0`, targeting exactly the `OpticalConstructor.Tests.fsproj` host this slice creates. Authoring that test host here is therefore what makes the gate resolve and pass before slice 001's roster runs; the slice owns the gate's runtime target, while the descriptor file itself is gate-keeper-owned repo infrastructure (a worker MUST NOT add or edit `.gates/**` descriptors — `arc-runner.user-md`). This file is a necessary realization of the gate roster, not a parent files-in-scope bullet.

## Non-requirements

- No domain types, orchestration logic, units conversions, materials, sources, charts, optimization, persistence, or UI pages — those land in later slices. Placeholder/empty compilable modules only.
- MUST NOT add a sixth top-level app project (§A.1).
- MUST NOT repurpose or modify `OpticalModel.fsproj` (§A.1).
- MUST NOT reference, link, or build against the FuncUI clone (`C:\GitHub\Avalonia.FuncUI.Clone\`) or resolve its linking mechanism (constraint 5 / §A.6 / §A.9).
- MUST NOT route any linear algebra through ALGLIB, nor wire `ExtremeNumericsMath` into the numerics path (§A.8).
- MUST NOT introduce a new C# project (constraint 1).
- The `.gitignore` edit for `*.binz`/`*.autosave` is owned by slice 012 (Part I sidecars), not here.

